statement:
Find the first three nonzero terms in the power-series representation in
powers of $x$ (i.e. the Maclaurin series) for

\begin{align*}\int_0^x \frac{t}{1-t^8}\,dt.\end{align*}

sols:
Recall the following Maclaurin series expansion

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{1-x} = 1 + x + x^{2} + x^{3} + ... = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}x^{n}\end{align*}

Now plugging in $x = t^{8}$ gives

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{1-t^{8}} = 1 + t^{8} + t^{16} + t^{24} + ... = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}t^{8n}\end{align*}

and then multiplying by $t$ gives

\begin{align*}\frac{t}{1-t^{8}} = t + t^{9} + t^{17} + t^{25} + ... = \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}t^{8n+1}\end{align*}

Hence, the first three nonzero terms are

\begin{align*}\displaystyle t, t^{9}, t^{17}.\end{align*}

Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\int_0^x\frac{t}{1-t^8}\textrm{d}t &\approx\int_0^x\left(t+t^9+t^{17}\right)\textrm{d}t\\
&=\left.\left(\frac{t^2}{2}+\frac{t^{10}}{10}+\frac{t^{18}}{18}\right)\right|_0^x\\
&=\frac{x^2}{2}+\frac{x^{10}}{10}+\frac{x^{18}}{18}\end{align*}

produces the first three non-zero terms of the desired integral.
